 @Galo Aguirre  "this couldn't be the case for these carbon capture contraptions?" Its possible but unlikely. Or maybe more to the point solving the cost prohibitive part of direct carbon capture would also lower the cost of competing solutions. The primary cost driver is  cheap renewable energy. And we are already fairly close to the maximum expected efficiencies of pulling carbon out of the air. This is very different than the situation with solar panels 20 years ago. They were cost constrained by efficiencies well below the theoretical maximums and manufacturing costs. And of course if you solve the cheap renewable energy problem then why not just replace the fossil fuel emitting plants. 

Carbon capture may be important for handling a few specific high value carbon sources. For example it can be used to make green aircraft fuel. But this is sort of the last hardest problem. There are many many problems that can be solved much cheaper for much higher impact. And it may be worth some level of investment now so we will be ready for this.

The big worry though is that these projects will be used as excuses to continue emitting. People who just want to profit off of fossil fuels will point to carbon capture as a reason its ok. People not very interested will take their word for it, not realizing that it will almost certainly be more expensive than investment in better batteries and electric grids. This is why its really really important for people like Gates and Elon to be super clear about their intentions for the technology. We say this exact same BS with clean coal.

